9c819aa8eaa65430e14e67"},"toolResults":[{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_cONHYDMz3p6T1RFAaGTscLDH|fc_09e1a19d9e220e560169de0ad47e2c819ab43d0ecb22887be1","toolName":"bash","content":[{"type":"text","text":"     1\t# Task Spec: refactor-agnostic\n     2\t\n     3\t## Objectives\n     4\t\n     5\t- Extract a **platform-agnostic multicodex-core** from the current monolithic `index.ts` so account state, selection, rotation policy, usage caching, and token refresh logic can be reused outside the pi extension runtime.\n     6\t- Keep the **pi adapter** thin: it should own commands, provider registration, UI prompts/notifications, browser-launch behavior, and stream/event translation.\n     7\t- Preserve current user-visible behavior and docs for the existing pi extension surface while enabling future non-pi consumers such as Mnemos bridges/gateways.\n     8\t- Create stable seams by **behavior**, not by arbitrary file size.\n     9\t\n    10\t## Non-goals\n    11\t\n    12\t- No change to the core Codex selection policy unless explicitly called out in tests and docs.\n    13\t- No redesign of the existing pi command UX in this task.\n    14\t- No gateway/server implementation in this task beyond interfaces or stubs that prove the core can be reused.\n    15\t- No migration to a new protocol or API surface for ChatGPT/Codex requests.\n    16\t- No broad package/workspace restructuring unless required to keep the core importable; the first pass should prefer module boundaries over repo re-layout.\n    17\t- In this first pass, `multicodex-core` and `multicodex-pi-adapter` refer to logical module boundaries inside the existing package unless a stronger packaging split is required by tests or distribution constraints.\n    18\t\n    19\t## Current-state analysis\n    20\t\n    21\t### Current repo state\n    22\t\n    23\t- The current repo root is effectively a **single entrypoint**: `index.ts` contains the whole behavior surface.\n    24\t- `index.test.ts` currently locks in the observed behavior for:\n    25\t  - quota error classification\n    26\t  - provider mirroring\n    27\t  - usage response parsing\n    28\t  - selection heuristics\n    29\t  - manual account preference in streaming\n    30\t  - quota-triggered rotation before any output\n    31\t- The current README exposes a very small public surface:\n    32\t  - `/multicodex-login`\n    33\t  - `/multicodex-use`\n    34\t  - `/multicodex-status`\n    35\t  - local dev install via `pi -e ./index.ts`\n    36\t- For this task, `/multicodex-use` is the canonical existing manual-switch command. Any rename such as `/multicodex-switch` is out of scope unless README, tests, and compatibility behavior are updated together.\n    37\t- The monolith couples together:\n    38\t  - filesystem persistence\n    39\t  - token refresh\n    40\t  - usage fetching\n    41\t  - selection policy\n    42\t  - provider registration\n    43\t  - stream retry/rotation\n    44\t  - browser login launch\n    45\t  - error message formatting\n    46\t\n    47\t### Reference implementation signal\n    48\t\n    49\tThe reference source under `.agents/sources/pi-multicodex/` already demonstrates a useful seam split:\n    50\t\n    51\t- `storage.ts`\n    52\t- `selection.ts`\n    53\t- `usage.ts`\n    54\t- `account-manager.ts`\n    55\t- `stream-wrapper.ts`\n    56\t- `provider.ts`\n    57\t- `commands.ts`\n    58\t- `hooks.ts`\n    59\t- `status.ts`\n    60\t- `auth.ts`\n    61\t- `usage-client.ts`\n    62\t- `refresh-race.test.ts`\n    63\t\n    64\tThat reference is **useful for boundaries**, but not all of its policy should be copied blindly:\n    65\t\n    66\t- the source has a richer command/status surface than the current README\n    67\t- the source has a lower-usage tie-breaker that is not currently part of the repo-root behavior contract\n    68\t- the source introduces pi-auth/imported-auth behaviors that are adapter-specific and should not leak into the platform-agnostic core\n    69\t\n    70\t### Current extraction problem\n    71\t\n    72\tThe current `index.ts` mixes three layers that should be separated:\n    73\t\n    74\t1. **pure domain logic**\n    75\t2. **storage / refresh orchestration**\n    76\t3. **pi runtime integration**\n    77\t\n    78\tThis makes it hard to reuse the account-selection and rotation logic in any non-pi context.\n    79\t\n    80\t## Behavior parity contract\n    81\t\n    82\tThis refactor must preserve the following behaviors unless a test and doc update explicitly changes them.\n    83\t\n    84\t### 1) Account selection\n    85\t\n    86\t- Manual account override wins when available.\n    87\t- Auto-selection excludes exhausted accounts.\n    88\t- Selection prefers accounts with **untouched** usage (`0%` in both windows) when available.\n    89\t- If no untouched account is available, selection should prefer the account with the earliest eligible weekly reset among the usable set.\n    90\t- If usage is unavailable for all candidates, fall back to a random available account.\n    91\t- Selection must honor an explicit `excludeEmails` set during retries.\n    92\t\n    93\t### 2) Usage parsing and refresh\n    94\t\n    95\t- Parse the `wham/usage` payload into a normalized snapshot with primary/secondary windows.\n    96\t- Convert `reset_at` seconds to millisecond timestamps.\n    97\t- Cache usage snapshots for **5 minutes** by default.\n    98\t- Retry transient usage fetch failures with bounded backoff.\n    99\t- Preserve the current retry policy: 2 retries, backoff roughly `300ms` then `900ms`.\n   100\t- Abort-like failures should not poison the cache path and should be treated as cancellations, not hard failures.\n   101\t\n   102\t### 3) Token refresh\n   103\t\n   104\t- Tokens are considered valid if they have at least 5 minutes of remaining life.\n   105\t- Expired tokens must be refreshed before use.\n   106\t- Successful refresh persists updated credentials back to managed storage.\n   107\t- Per-account refresh deduplication is a valid improvement for this task, but it is not part of the current monolith's proven behavior contract. If added, it must be treated as an intentional enhancement with dedicated tests.\n   108\t\n   109\t### 4) Quota/error rotation\n   110\t\n   111\t- A quota/rate-limit error before any streamed output should trigger account cooldown + rotation + retry.\n   112\t- Once any output has been forwarded, the stream must not silently rotate; it should forward the error and end.\n   113\t- The retry loop should remain bounded; do not create unbounded account cycling.\n   114\t- On quota hit, the failed account must be marked exhausted until its next reset time, or a fallback cooldown if no reset is known.\n   115\t\n   116\t### 5) Provider/adapter behavior\n   117\t\n   118\t- The provider must still mirror the underlying `openai-codex` model metadata.\n   119\t- The stream wrapper must still inject the selected account identifier into request headers.\n   120\t- The adapter must still rewrite provider metadata back to the caller-facing provider ID on events.\n   121\t- If the pi provider is unavailable, startup should warn/skip registration rather than crash.\n   122\t\n   123\t### 6) Public API compatibility\n   124\t\n   125\t- Keep existing root exports working during the transition, especially those used by current tests and external consumers.\n   126\t- If new core exports are introduced, the old names should remain available via a compatibility barrel until the migration is complete.\n   127\t\n   128\t## Target architecture\n   129\t\n   130\t### A) `multicodex-core`\n   131\t\n   132\tThe core boundary should be usable without pi extension runtime imports.\n   133\t\n   134\t#### Owns\n   135\t\n   136\t- account and storage models\n   137\t- account CRUD and active/manual resolution\n   138\t- selection policy and retry exclusion logic\n   139\t- token validity/refresh orchestration\n   140\t- usage snapshot cache and refresh policy\n   141\t- quota exhaustion and cooldown bookkeeping\n   142\t- state change notification hooks for adapters/UI\n   143\t- storage migration normalization and schema validation\n   144\t\n   145\t#### Must not own\n   146\t\n   147\t- pi command registration\n   148\t- pi UI notifications/prompts\n   149\t- browser-launch logic\n   150\t- provider mirroring / model registration\n   151\t- assistant message event shaping\n   152\t- any dependency on `@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent`\n   153\t\n   154\t#### Dependency model\n   155\t\n   156\tCore should accept injected collaborators rather than importing pi-specific APIs:\n   157\t\n   158\t- `StorageAdapter` for load/save\n   159\t- `TokenRefresher` for refresh-token exchange\n   160\t- `UsageClient` for usage fetches\n   161\t- `clock`/`random` overrides for deterministic testing\n   162\t- optional `logger`/`warning` callbacks for non-fatal diagnostics\n   163\t\n   164\t### B) `multicodex-pi-adapter`\n   165\t\n   166\tThe pi adapter boundary should be the only place that touches pi extension APIs.\n   167\t\n   168\t#### Owns\n   169\t\n   170\t- default extension export\n   171\t- `/multicodex-login`, `/multicodex-use`, `/multicodex-status` command wiring\n   172\t- provider registration for `openai-codex-responses`\n   173\t- stream bridging and retry/rotation orchestration for pi requests\n   174\t- UI prompts, selects, confirms, and notifications\n   175\t- browser-open behavior for the OAuth login flow\n   176\t- session hooks (`session_start`, `session_switch`, etc.)\n   177\t\n   178\t#### Must not own\n   179\t\n   180\t- account storage model rules\n   181\t- selection policy decisions\n   182\t- usage parsing logic\n   183\t- token refresh policy\n   184\t- quota bookkeeping policy\n   185\t\n   186\t### C) Optional gateway layer\n   187\t\n   188\tNot required for this task, but the core should be shaped so a future gateway can drive it with its own request protocol.\n   189\t\n   190\t- gateway should reuse the same selection/refresh/storage core\n   191\t- gateway should implement its own transport and streaming protocol\n   192\t- gateway should not need any pi-specific code\n   193\t\n   194\t## Module extraction map from current `index.ts`\n   195\t\n   196\t> This is the concrete first-pass map for splitting the current monolith by behavior seam.\n   197\t\n   198\t| Current region / functions | Target module | Notes |\n   199\t| --- | --- | --- |\n   200\t| `isQuotaErrorMessage`, `getErrorMessage`, `isAbortLikeError`, `getUsageHttpStatus`, `isRetryableUsageError`, `sleepWithSignal` | `core/errors.ts` and `core/retry.ts` | Keep retry classification pure and testable. |\n   201\t| `resolveCodexOAuthFns`, `loginOpenAICodexCompat`, `refreshOpenAICodexTokenCompat`, `openLoginInBrowser` | `adapter/pi/oauth.ts` and `adapter/pi/browser.ts` | pi-specific OAuth/browser integration stays out of core. |\n   202\t| `createErrorAssistantMessage`, `withProvider`, `createLinkedAbortController`, `createTimeoutController` | `adapter/pi/stream-utils.ts` | Event shaping and abort linking belong to the adapter. |\n   203\t| `normalizeUsedPercent`, `normalizeResetAt`, `parseUsageWindow`, `parseCodexUsageResponse`, `isUsageUntouched`, `getNextResetAt`, `getWeeklyResetAt` | `core/usage.ts` | Keep usage normalization and reset selection pure and platform-agnostic. |\n   204\t| `formatResetAt` | `adapter/pi/status.ts` (or adapter-local formatting module) | Human-readable status formatting is presentation logic and should stay out of core. |\n   205\t| `fetchCodexUsage` | `core/usage-client.ts` or injected `UsageClient` implementation | Core should own the default logic, but the HTTP client must be injectable. |\n   206\t| `Account`, `StorageData`, `isAccountAvailable`, `pickRandomAccount`, `pickEarliestWeeklyResetAccount`, `pickBestAccount` | `core/types.ts`, `core/selection.ts` | Selection is pure domain logic. |\n   207\t| `AccountManager` (load/save, cache, refresh, cooldown, active/manual state, refresh dedupe, token refresh, quota handling) | `core/account-manager.ts` | This is the main reusable runtime abstraction. |\n   208\t| `getOpenAICodexMirror`, `buildMulticodexProviderConfig` | `adapter/pi/provider.ts` | Mirror and provider registration are adapter-only. |\n   209\t| `multicodexExtension` default export | `adapter/pi/index.ts` | Root entrypoint remains the pi extension. |\n   210\t| `createStreamWrapper` | `adapter/pi/stream-wrapper.ts` | Keeps request rotation close to the provider bridge. |\n   211\t\n   212\t### Recommended file layout\n   213\t\n   214\t- `core/index.ts` â€” public core barrel\n   215\t- `core/types.ts`\n   216\t- `core/selection.ts`\n   217\t- `core/usage.ts`\n   218\t- `core/usage-client.ts`\n   219\t- `core/storage.ts`\n   220\t- `core/account-manager.ts`\n   221\t- `core/errors.ts`\n   222\t- `core/retry.ts`\n   223\t- `adapter/pi/index.ts`\n   224\t- `adapter/pi/provider.ts`\n   225\t- `adapter/pi/stream-wrapper.ts`\n   226\t- `adapter/pi/commands.ts`\n   227\t- `adapter/pi/hooks.ts`\n   228\t- `adapter/pi/status.ts`\n   229\t- `adapter/pi/oauth.ts`\n   230\t- `adapter/pi/browser.ts`\n   231\t- `adapter/pi/stream-utils.ts`\n   232\t- root `index.ts` as a compatibility barrel and default export shim during migration\n   233\t\n   234\t## Public interfaces\n   235\t\n   236\t### Root compatibility exports\n   237\t\n   238\tThe root `index.ts` compatibility barrel must continue to export the names that are exported today and used by the current tests:\n   239\t\n   240\t- `Account`\n   241\t- `AccountManager`\n   242\t- `CodexUsageSnapshot`\n   243\t- `ProviderModelDef`\n   244\t- `buildMulticodexProviderConfig`\n   245\t- `createStreamWrapper`\n   246\t- `getNextResetAt`\n   247\t- `getOpenAICodexMirror`\n   248\t- `getWeeklyResetAt`\n   249\t- `isQuotaErrorMessage`\n   250\t- `isUsageUntouched`\n   251\t- `parseCodexUsageResponse`\n   252\t- `pickBestAccount`\n   253\t- default export: the pi extension function\n   254\t\n   255\tNew core-only interfaces such as `StorageAdapter`, `UsageClient`, `TokenRefresher`, `StorageData`, or `createAccountManager` may be introduced, but they are not required to be root-stable in this task unless tests and docs are updated to make them public.\n   256\t\n   257\t### Core behavior surface required for adapter parity\n   258\t\n   259\tIf `AccountManager` remains a class, it must support the methods the current adapter behavior depends on:\n   260\t\n   261\t- `getAccounts()`\n   262\t- `getAccount(email)`\n   263\t- `getActiveAccount()`\n   264\t- `getManualAccount()`\n   265\t- `hasManualAccount()`\n   266\t- `getAvailableManualAccount(options?)`\n   267\t- `setActiveAccount(email)`\n   268\t- `setManualAccount(email)`\n   269\t- `clearManualAccount()`\n   270\t- `addOrUpdateAccount(email, creds)`\n   271\t- `getCachedUsage(email)`\n   272\t- `refreshUsageForAccount(account, options?)`\n   273\t- `refreshUsageForAllAccounts(options?)`\n   274\t- `refreshUsageIfStale(accounts, options?)`\n   275\t- `activateBestAccount(options?)`\n   276\t- `ensureValidToken(account)`\n   277\t- `handleQuotaExceeded(account, options?)`\n   278\t\n   279\tWarning and diagnostics behavior may remain an injected callback or small logger surface rather than requiring a broader `onStateChange(...)` API in this task.\n   280\t\n   281\t### Adapter exports\n   282\t\n   283\tKeep the following adapter exports available for tests and compatibility:\n   284\t\n   285\t- default export: the pi extension function\n   286\t- `buildMulticodexProviderConfig`\n   287\t- `createStreamWrapper`\n   288\t- `getOpenAICodexMirror`\n   289\t- `ProviderModelDef`\n   290\t\n   291\t## Storage and migration strategy\n   292\t\n   293\t### Canonical shape\n   294\t\n   295\tThe canonical storage shape should be versioned and stable:\n   296\t\n   297\t- `version`\n   298\t- `accounts[]`\n   299\t- `activeEmail?`\n   300\t- optional `$schema` metadata if the file format benefits from editor support\n   301\t\n   302\tAccount records should preserve:\n   303\t\n   304\t- `email`\n   305\t- `accessToken`\n   306\t- `refreshToken`\n   307\t- `expiresAt`\n   308\t- `accountId?`\n   309\t- `lastUsed?`\n   310\t- `quotaExhaustedUntil?`\n   311\t- `needsReauth?` if the core includes auth-failure tracking\n   312\t\n   313\t### Migration behavior\n   314\t\n   315\t- Treat storage migration as **additive and idempotent**.\n   316\t- Required compatibility input for this task is the current monolith's file at `~/.pi/agent/multicodex.json` with the legacy unversioned shape `{ accounts, activeEmail? }`.\n   317\t- The pi adapter owns the default file path; the core must receive storage through an injected adapter and must not hard-code the pi path.\n   318\t- Support for additional legacy shapes from the reference implementation is optional unless this task adds explicit fixtures and regression tests for them.\n   319\t- Corrupt-file salvage is optional scope; if implemented, the spec/tests must define exactly which fields are salvageable and what happens to malformed records.\n   320\t- On successful load of a supported legacy file, write back the canonical versioned format.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776159445093}]}
